05414nam a22006495i 9780300237580DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20221998ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002375807 a10.12987/97803002375802doi  a(DE-B1597)625826  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aPR5827.I67bW55 1998eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a828/.8092231 aMcCormack, Jerusha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWilde the Irishman /cJerusha McCormack. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor nearly a century, Oscar Wilde (1854-1900) has been seen primarily as a "British" writer—a description that ignores his Irish parentage and the experience of the first twenty years of his life. In this vigorous study, seventeen leading Irish artists, critics, and cultural commentators explore the neglected theme of Wilde’s Irishness. Viewing Wilde from a range of unusual and arresting angles, the contributors assess what difference it makes to perceive him as Irish, or Anglo-Irish, rather than as a British writer.The intention is to restore the author to his native context and to the rich and complicated cultural inheritance of an Irishman who spent much of his life in England. In its first section, the book presents a sequence of critical essays by such celebrated Irish writers, critics, and commentators as Derek Kiberd, Angela Bourke, Bernard O’Donoghue, and Fintan O’Toole. The second section aims to give some indication of the creative response to Wilde by some of Ireland’s most gifted artists: among them, poets, playwrights, sculptors, a short story writer, and an actor. The book closes with Seamus Heaney’s remarkable dedication of the Wilde window at Poet’s Corner, Westminster Abbey. While the contributors to this volume reach a consensus about the essential Irishness of Wilde, they subvert the comfortable categories in which Wilde generally has been placed and highlight the difficulties of evaluating him within a cultural context. The book sets Wilde within the tradition of other formidable Irish writers, including Joyce, Beckett, Shaw, and Yeats—a tradition from which he has been previously excluded—and restores him to his rightful place as an Irish writer of rare, if not uncomplicated, distinction.Contributors • Angela Bourke • Owen Dudley Edwards • John Wilson Foster • Seamus Heaney • Declan Kiberd • Tom Kilroy • Derek Mahon • Jerusha McCormack • W.J. McCormack • Frank McGuinness • Paula Murphy • Bernard O’Donoghue • Fintan O’Toole • Gabriel Rosenstock • Alan Stanford • Deirdre Toomey • Victoria White  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aNational characteristics, Irish, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aBourke, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Owen Dudley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, John Wilson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeaney, Seamus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiberd, Declan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahon, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCormack, Jerusha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCormack, W. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGuinness, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Donoghue, Bernard,